Some of the sort of headlines were high-income countries, so Sweden, the USA, for example,

30
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:33.000
scored higher on some of the more material aspects of flourishing and so things like finance,

31
00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:38.000
middle-income countries, so Mexico, for example, scored more highly on things like

32
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:42.000
meaning of relationships and kindness and social cohesion.

33
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
Claudia asks about the study's most interesting nuggets.

34
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.000
A nugget means a small piece of something good like wisdom or precious, like a nugget of gold.

35
00:02:52.000 --> 00:03:00.000
While richer countries scored higher on material happiness, middle-income countries did better in terms of kindness and social connection.

36
00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:06.000
Though interesting differences between men and women, for example, in Japan, women flourished more than men,

37
00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:14.000
while in Brazil, the opposite was true, and across all countries flourishing increased after the age of 50.

38
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:17.000
So does flourishing depend on your nationality?

39
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:21.000
Or are there things anyone can do to feel happier wherever they live?

40
00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:28.000
Let's find out, as Claudia Hammond talks more with Peter Olosaga for BBC Radio 4's All In The Mind.

41
00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:32.000
So what can any of us do to help ourselves to flourish us the big question?

42
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:36.000
Well, there's a few things that we can do, and they are supported by research as well.

43
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.000
So things that are simple as just practicing gratitude.

44
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:44.000
Alright, being thankful for what we have as a way of increasing the amount of flourishing that we have in our lives,

45
00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:49.000
showing kindness, which helps us to develop connection with other people.

46
00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:53.000
And just celebrating our own accomplishments, I think we spoken on the program before about savoring.

47
00:03:53.000 --> 00:03:55.000
Oh yeah, we have, yes, savoring that is good moments.

48
00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:59.000
Exactly, just taking the time to really appreciate some of those small wins.

49
00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:06.000
Claudia asks the big question, in other words, the thing everyone would like to know how do people flourish?

50
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:13.000
There are simple things anyone can do, starting with grassitude, feeling thankful and appreciative for what you have.

51
00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:19.000
Being kind and connecting with others are also indicators of flourishing.

52
00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:22.000
The study also recommends savoring life.

53
00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:27.000
To save it means to fully enjoy something by experiencing it slowly and mindfully.

54
00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:32.000
It involves taking time out to enjoy good moments, to stop and smell the roses, as we say.

55
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:35.000
This links to the phrase small wins.

56
00:04:35.000 --> 00:04:41.000
Mine achievements or successes which bring you a little closer to your long-term goals in life.

57
00:04:41.000 --> 00:04:47.000
There's an old saying, a journey of a thousand miles starts with a single step.

58
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:53.000
And savoring each small win along the way is vital to flourishing.

59
00:04:53.000 --> 00:05:00.000
Flourishing seems to be a big new idea in some countries at least, which reminds me of your question, Georgie.

60
00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:09.000
Yes, Phil, I asked you, in the global flourishing study, which country came out on top, in the options where Indonesia, Denmark or Brazil.

61
00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:11.000
And I said Denmark.

62
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:14.000
Which Phil, I'm afraid that is the wrong answer.

63
00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:16.000
The correct answer is Indonesia.

64
